Data Exploration Analysis of Crime Victim Data¶

A. C. Coffin¶

11/10/2023¶

Northwestern Missouri State University¶

MS Data Analytics Capstone¶

Data Exploration is critical to this project as victim data is often incomplete. In total there are 6 data sets that are utilized in this project, each of these have been loaded into an SQL database. Through the use of an SQL database, it is possible to pull information from multiple sets when referencing data pulled from the National Crime Victim Survey (N-Dash). In order to pull the information from the N-Dash multiple queries were made from the source and compiled into four data sets. All queries were exported from the SQL server as CSV files. Complete list of sources:

  • New York Police Department Open Portal
  • N-Dash Bureau of Justices Statistics

Each of these regions has been selected based on geographical, socioeconomic diversity, industry level and population. Each of the individual regions has been analyzed first and then the NCVS data.

Libraries & Files:¶

Data from the N-Dash has been stored as separate unionized sets after being processed through SQL. All original data pulled from this database has been added to the file labeled Raw Data. This notebook contains the DEA for the selected cities and states. See other notebook for data pertaining to the NCVS Data.

Crime Data is classified into separate categories which are either noted with an offense description or associated with a Number. These numbers are often called NIBRS Codes or Key Codes. Each provides a numerical way to categorize data. In this instance a KY_CD 578 is a Harassment Code. The most common crime that women are victims to is Harassment 2, which is considered a Personal Crime. Personal Crimes include sexual assault, robbery, aggravated assault, simple assault, and murder. When looking at the most common crimes women are often victims of according to the NYPD the most common crimes are Personal. When examining the role of victims in crimes it can also be noted that a large number of women are often victims of assisting a felony, disorderly conduct in a public setting or a miscellaneous penal law. Each of these is not traditionally covered in NCVS data, but still relevant to understanding the victimology of women.

The data for this project ranges from 01/01/1993 to 01/01/2024 as this is the same span of time that data from the NCVS was available. However, not all the records are in this data set as the NYPD is still cataloguing older cases that haven't been fully digitized. As a result, in terms of recent crime trends the data plotted is from 2021 to 2023. During 2019 to 2021 the COVID-19 Pandemic resulted in a lock down throughout New York State. This resulted in a decrease in reports made to the police for a variety of reasons including first responders being instructed to avoid physical contact with individuals unless they had PPE and as many areas that are considered public or gathering locations were also closed individuals were unable to interact within wider social demographics.

There is a negative correlation between age and the probability that an individual will be a victim of a crime. However when looking at the possibility of a specific type of crime being more prevelant than another in terms of key code, there is a negative correlation between the type of crime and age. This when combined with the information the the largest number of crimes reported are between the ages of 25-44, in terms fo the type of crime being a correlating factor is lower in female victims in terms of age. Crime is complex and dependent on a number of factors such as socioeconomic status, location, age, physical attributes, and even marital/ relationship status.

NCVS Data:¶

The National Crime Victim Survey has a massive amount of data utilized annually. As a result, each year is summarized as a numeric mean for the number of cases reported through the survey. Each survey reports from households age, race, gender, crimes that they have experienced, injuries, whether the crime was reported and more. For this Project we will be looking at age, regional data and the type of crime. In terms of regional data, the breakdown of specific types of crimes such as robbery, assault and sexual assault are in separate categories based on their NCIC numbers. The data pertaining to age is more general. The NCVS also records data from minors as old as 12 and groups ages into 8 categories.

Characteristics of the Data:¶

Data Sets that are labeled segmented means that crimes such as robbery and assault are clearly noted. Where as general sets only differenciate violent crime from assaults. This is a result of how the data was pulled from the NCVS as a series of quieries to the N-Dash.

Nationally women between the ages of 25 to 34 and 35 to 49 are more likely to experience simple assault. It is also true that a larger number of victims within these groups also reported a higher number of violent crimes. This falls in line with the general statistic that those within the 25 to 34 age group are more likely to experience a violent crime according to Doerner. The group that is mainly concern is the large number of children under 18 that experience a form of Simple Assault. This age group is difficult to gauge due to the nature of the crimes committed with children as victims.
